    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Wary Eye on Putin</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Elliott A Cohen letter, commenting on May 9 editorial on inauguration of Vladimir V Putin as Russia's new president, says trust and confidence in Putin, who was former KGB official, warrants guarded eye (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''President Vladimir Putin'' (editorial, May 9):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''President Vladimir Putin'' (editorial, May 9):</p>
        <p>Trust and confidence in the new Russian president, a former K.G.B. official, warrants a guarded eye for now. The weight of President Boris N. Yeltsin's power assured Mr. Putin's ascension. Control of television presentation reinforced a meek challenge. Explosions in apartment buildings in which scores were killed set the tone for a longing for stability. Excessive force against Chechen guerrillas and civilians was in part an election ploy to demonstrate swift and deliberate strength.</p>
        <p>Moreover, Mr. Putin's choice of Mikhail Kasyanov as prime minister  reflects less a commitment to genuine economic reform than concern about Russia's debts and an expectation of continued loans.</p>
        <p>ELLIOTT A. COHEN  Santa Barbara, Calif., May 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
